replies.bodyText:
Good catch.
I think, the simplest way to fix this problem is to use the fact that loggerFactory accesses are guarded with CHM (mapLoggers) operations and we could use CHM's atomicity guarantees for the deletion:
    @Override
    public void removeLogger(@Nonnull String name) {
        checkNotNull(name, "name must not be null");
        mapLoggers.computeIfPresent(name, (k, v) -> {
            loggerFactory.removeLogger(name);
            // delete the entry
            return null;
        });        
    }

